                <h3>Shorshe Carbonara</h3>
                <p>A refined interpretation of the Italian classic, elevated with premium Bengali mustard and delicate seasonal influences. This signature creation exemplifies our commitment to culinary excellence and innovative fusion.</p>
                
                <div class="chef-note">
                    "This dish represents the perfect harmony between Bengali and Italian culinary traditions. The pungent complexity of mustard creates an unexpected but delightful counterpoint to the richness of the traditional carbonara."
                </div>
                
                <h4>INGREDIENTS</h4>
                <ul class="ingredients-list">
                    <li>200g artisanal spaghetti alla chitarra</li>
                    <li>2 tbsp hand-ground Bengali black mustard seeds</li>
                    <li>2 tbsp first-press mustard oil</li>
                    <li>2 farm-fresh organic egg yolks</li>
                    <li>50g aged Parmesan Reggiano, microplaned</li>
                    <li>4 slices heritage-breed pancetta, julienned</li>
                    <li>2 cloves Himalayan garlic, minced</li>
                    <li>Green Bhut Jolokia chilies, to taste</li>
                    <li>Fleur de sel and freshly cracked tellicherry pepper</li>
                    <li>Micro coriander for garnish</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h4>PREPARATION</h4>
                <ol class="steps-list">
                    <li>Cook the spaghetti in lightly salted spring water until perfectly al dente. Reserve 60ml of the pasta water.</li>
                    <li>In a stone mortar, grind mustard seeds with a small amount of filtered water to create a smooth, aromatic paste.</li>
                    <li>In a chilled copper bowl, gently whisk egg yolks with microplaned Parmesan until velvety.</li>
                    <li>Heat mustard oil in a heavy-bottomed pan and render the pancetta until delicately crisp.</li>
                    <li>Add minced garlic and finely chopped chilies, sauté until fragrant, approximately 30 seconds.</li>
                    <li>Incorporate the cooked pasta, tossing gently to coat each strand.</li>
                    <li>Remove from heat and gradually introduce the egg mixture, stirring continuously to achieve a silken emulsion.</li>
                    <li>Fold in the mustard paste with precision, adjusting consistency with reserved pasta water if necessary.</li>
                    <li>Season with fleur de sel and freshly cracked pepper to taste.</li>
                    <li>Plate immediately, garnishing with micro coriander and a final whisper of Parmesan.</li>
                </ol>
                
